# Research: PR #630 GHAS + CodeRabbit findings — full fix/rewrite plan

**Date**: 2026-05-05 14:15 +10:00
**Git Commit**: 2565270fac554cc02769ba6012eeb7c2cd9ae5d6
**Branch**: desktop-portless-runtime-batch
**PR**: https://github.com/lightfastai/lightfast/pull/630 — *Desktop runtime-config refactor + decouple related-projects*

## Research Question

Catalog every issue and comment raised by **github-advanced-security[bot]** and **coderabbitai[bot]** on PR #630, verify each against the current code, and propose a concrete fix or rewrite for every one.

## Summary

PR #630 has **18 distinct findings**:

- **1 GHAS code-scan alert** (alert #99, `js/clear-text-logging`) — false-positive but worth dismissing or rewording.
- **14 CodeRabbit inline actionable comments** — including 2 🔴 *Critical*, 5 🟠 *Major* (4 marked `[blocker]`), 7 🟡 *Minor* (3 marked `[blocker]`).
- **3 CodeRabbit "outside-diff" comments** — 1 *Major* (refactor), 1 *Major* (vendor-rule violation), 1 *Minor* `[blocker]` (formatter).
- **2 CodeRabbit nitpicks** — duplication + unpinned CLIs.

The findings cluster into **5 themes**:

1. **CI/format hygiene (8 items)** — Biome import/attribute/property-order + formatter failures. Fast fix: `pnpm fix`.
2. **Auth race-condition pattern (3 items)** — `hasInitRef` / `hasActivatedRef` / `hasStartedRef` are latched **before** the async work runs, so any transient failure bricks the component permanently. Same anti-pattern in three files.
3. **Open-redirect surface (1 item)** — `getRedirectUrl` accepts arbitrary `redirect_url` from `FormData`. Real risk, but a naïve "paths starting with `/`" fix breaks the desktop-auth handoff (which intentionally uses `https://lightfast.localhost/desktop/auth?...`). Needs a host allowlist. **Plumbing introduced on this PR (commit `ccafedc53`).**
4. **DB-client correctness + abstraction (3 items)** — `withLocalBatch`'s `Promise.all` violates atomicity in local Postgres path; `db/app/src/client.ts` and `api/app/package.json` directly import `@neondatabase/serverless` / `postgres` instead of routing through `@vendor/db`. **`withLocalBatch` introduced on this PR (commit `1d14f390d`)** when local dev moved from neon-http to postgres-js. Production is still atomic (verified at the wire level).
5. **Preview-deploy URL resolution (1 item)** — `apps/platform/src/lib/project-urls.ts` uses `defaultHost = "https://lightfast.ai"` for any non-development env. **Confirmed broken in production right now (not theoretical):** `VERCEL_RELATED_PROJECTS` is absent on both Vercel projects in preview AND production, so every preview tRPC call from app→platform 403s. Migration commit `f51668a81` (this PR) carried the latent bug forward intact.

**Cross-cutting insight**: 6 of the highest-impact findings (Theme 2.x, 3.1, 4.1, 5.1) were *introduced* on PR #630 itself. The PR's refactor scope ("Desktop runtime-config refactor + decouple related-projects") explains why — every theme matches a subsystem the refactor touched (auth island components, redirect_url propagation, DB client local path, dev-proxy migration). The reviews collectively caught the regressions the refactor introduced.

## Detailed Findings

### Theme 1 — CI / format hygiene (8 items)

All flagged by CodeRabbit because Biome (`pnpm check`) is currently failing on this branch. A single `pnpm fix` (ultracite) followed by a commit clears every one. Listed individually for traceability:

| # | File | Lines | Rule |
|---|------|-------|------|
| 1.1 | `apps/app/next.config.ts` | 1-11 | `assist/source/organizeImports` |
| 1.2 | `apps/app/src/app/(auth)/sign-in/page.tsx` | 47-49 | Formatter (destructuring) |
| 1.3 | `apps/app/src/proxy.ts` | 14-24 | Formatter (object literal) |
| 1.4 | `apps/desktop/src/renderer/index.html` | 40-117 | Formatter (inline SVG) |
| 1.5 | `apps/desktop/src/renderer/src/react/entry.tsx` | 19-32 | Formatter (JSX whitespace) |
| 1.6 | `apps/desktop/src/renderer/src/react/user-menu.tsx` | 15-53 | `assist/source/useSortedAttributes` |
| 1.7 | `apps/desktop/src/renderer/src/styles.css` | 167-170 + 249-252, 254-257, 259-263, 380-383, 385-396, 409-417, 436-438 | `assist/source/useSortedProperties` |
| 1.8 | (within 1.6) — `aria-label="Settings"` mislabel | 15 | a11y semantics, not formatter |

**Verified live state.** Confirmed each violation is still present at HEAD (`2565270`):

- `apps/app/next.config.ts:10` imports `withProject` *between* `@vercel/microfrontends/next/config` (line 9) and `@vercel/toolbar/plugins/next` (line 11) — ordering broken.
- `apps/app/src/app/(auth)/sign-in/page.tsx:47-48` — destructure split across two lines mid-pattern.
- `apps/desktop/src/renderer/src/react/user-menu.tsx:15` — `<button type="button" className="item" aria-label="Settings">` props out of Biome's preferred order, plus the aria-label says "Settings" while the trigger opens the user menu.
- `apps/desktop/src/renderer/src/styles.css:167-170` — `.titlebar-drag` declares `height` before `flex-shrink` (Biome wants alphabetical).

**Proposed fix**

```bash
pnpm fix          # ultracite/biome autofix; covers 1.1-1.7
```

Then **manually** edit `user-menu.tsx:15`:

```diff
- <button type="button" className="item" aria-label="Settings">
+ <button type="button" className="item" aria-label="Open user menu">
```

(The autofix can't change the aria-label string itself — it's a semantic rename, not a sort order.)

---

### Theme 2 — Auth init/activation race conditions (3 items)

**Anti-pattern**: `hasXRef.current = true` is set *before* the code proves the dependent Clerk object (`signIn`, `signUp`, `session`) exists. Result: on the first render where Clerk reports `isLoaded === true` but the relevant hook field is still `null`, the guard latches forever and the user is stuck on an error state until they manually refresh.

#### 2.1 — `apps/app/src/app/(auth)/_components/otp-island.tsx:85-101` 🟠 Major [blocker]

```ts
85   React.useEffect(() => {
86     if (!isAuthLoaded) {
87       return;
88     }
89     if (hasInitRef.current) {
90       return;
91     }
92     hasInitRef.current = true;          // ← latches before checking signIn/signUp
93
94     async function init() {
95       if (mode === "sign-up" && ticket) {
96         if (!signUp) {
97           setError("Authentication is unavailable. ...");
98           return;                        // ← no retry possible
99         }
```

Same issue at the sign-in branch (line 146-153) and the sign-up-without-ticket branch (175-181).

**Proposed fix** — gate the latch on the actual prerequisites:

```ts
React.useEffect(() => {
  if (!isAuthLoaded) return;
  if (hasInitRef.current) return;

  // Only commit to "init has started" once we know Clerk is ready for our mode
  if (mode === "sign-in" && !signIn) return;
  if (mode === "sign-up" && !signUp) return;

  hasInitRef.current = true;
  // ...rest unchanged; the inner `if (!signIn)` / `if (!signUp)` guards can be removed
}, [email, mode, ticket, isAuthLoaded, signIn, signUp, handleClerkError, navigateToConsole]);
```

The effect already depends on `signIn` + `signUp` (line 225-226), so it will re-run when they populate.

#### 2.2 — `apps/app/src/app/(auth)/_components/session-activator.tsx:14-23` 🟠 Major [blocker]

```ts
14   const { isLoaded } = useAuth();
15   const { signIn } = useSignIn();
17   const hasActivatedRef = React.useRef(false);
19   React.useEffect(() => {
20     if (!isLoaded || hasActivatedRef.current) {
21       return;
22     }
23     hasActivatedRef.current = true;     // ← latches before checking signIn
24
25     async function activate() {
26       if (!signIn) {
27         setError("Sign-in failed. Please try again.");  // ← permanent
```

**Proposed fix**:

```diff
   React.useEffect(() => {
-    if (!isLoaded || hasActivatedRef.current) {
+    if (!isLoaded || !signIn || hasActivatedRef.current) {
       return;
     }
     hasActivatedRef.current = true;

     async function activate() {
-      if (!signIn) {
-        setError("Sign-in failed. Please try again.");
-        return;
-      }
       addBreadcrumb({ ... });
```

Effect deps already include `signIn` (line 62).

#### 2.3 — `apps/app/src/app/(app)/(user)/(pending-not-allowed)/_components/client-auth-bridge.tsx:26-56` 🟠 Major (outside-diff)

```ts
26   useEffect(() => {
27     if (!isLoaded || hasStartedRef.current) {
28       return;
29     }
30     if (!session) {
31       setStatus("error");                // OK — session check is before latch
32       return;
33     }
34     hasStartedRef.current = true;        // ← latched here
36     void (async () => {
37       try {
38         const token = await session.getToken(...);
                              // ← network call; on failure, no retry
```

This is a slightly different shape: a **transient** `getToken` failure (network blip, JWKS hiccup) leaves `hasStartedRef = true` and `status = "error"` permanently.

**Proposed fix** — split the duplicate-redirect guard from the in-flight guard:

```ts
const hasRedirectedRef = useRef(false);

useEffect(() => {
  if (!isLoaded) return;
  if (hasRedirectedRef.current) return;
  if (!session) {
    setStatus("error");
    return;
  }

  let cancelled = false;
  void (async () => {
    try {
      const token = await session.getToken(
        props.jwtTemplate ? { template: props.jwtTemplate } : undefined
      );
      if (cancelled) return;
      if (!token) { setStatus("error"); return; }

      const url = props.buildRedirectUrl({ token, searchParams });
      if (!url) { setStatus("error"); return; }

      hasRedirectedRef.current = true;     // latch only after success
      setStatus("redirecting");
      window.location.href = url;
    } catch {
      if (!cancelled) setStatus("error");
      // hasRedirectedRef NOT set → next render can retry when deps change
    }
  })();

  return () => { cancelled = true; };
}, [isLoaded, session, props, searchParams]);
```

> **Cross-cutting suggestion** (out of scope for the bot's review but worth noting): all three components use the same anti-pattern. Consider extracting a `useOneShotEffect(deps, predicate, fn)` helper into `apps/app/src/app/(auth)/_lib/` so the latch-after-success contract is encoded once.

---

### Theme 3 — Open-redirect surface

#### 3.1 — `apps/app/src/app/(auth)/_actions/sign-in.ts:11-14` 🟠 Major [blocker]

```ts
11   function getRedirectUrl(formData: FormData): string | null {
12     const value = formData.get("redirect_url");
13     return typeof value === "string" && value.length > 0 ? value : null;
14   }
```

Value flows through to `otp-island.tsx:40` where `window.location.href = redirectUrl ?? "/account/welcome"` — i.e. a fully arbitrary URL becomes a navigation. CodeRabbit's suggested fix (relative-path-only) is **incorrect for this codebase** because the desktop sign-in flow legitimately ships absolute URLs:

`apps/app/src/app/(auth)/_actions/sign-in.test.ts:62-65` — the test asserts that
```
redirect_url=https://lightfast.localhost/desktop/auth?state=abc&callback=...
```
must round-trip through the action. Tightening to `startsWith("/")` would break that test (and break desktop sign-in for real users).

**Introduction history (verified)**:
- The `redirect_url` *plumbing* through `initiateSignIn` was added on **PR #630 itself** in commit `ccafedc53` (*"fix(app): preserve mfe clerk auth flow"*). Before that commit, `initiateSignIn` did not propagate `redirect_url` at all — desktop users were always punted to `/account/welcome` after OTP, losing their `/desktop/auth?state&callback` deep-link. So the open-redirect surface was introduced *here*, fixing a real bug but creating this one.
- The desktop sign-in handoff itself dates to `1460005cc` (*"feat(desktop): Clerk sign-in via OS browser loopback + React renderer + Bearer tRPC"*). `33e262357` extracted the shared `ClientAuthBridge`. PKCE rewrite `b30d99975` replaced the loopback HTTP server with `lightfast://` custom-scheme URLs *for the desktop callback only*; the first hop (browser opens `<app-origin>/desktop/auth?...`) is unchanged.

**Hosts that legitimately appear in `redirect_url`** (enumerated by tracing every entry point):

1. **Same-origin paths from Clerk middleware** (`apps/app/src/proxy.ts:88-91`): `${pathname}${search}` — always starts with `/`. Examples: `/foo/bar`, `/desktop/auth?state=abc&callback=...`, `/cli/auth?port=...&state=...`.
2. **Absolute URLs from a different origin opening `/sign-in`** — only when the desktop main process calls `shell.openExternal(<appOrigin>/desktop/auth?...)` (`apps/desktop/src/main/auth-flow.ts:122-130`) using `getRuntimeConfig().appOrigin`, which resolves (via `apps/desktop/src/main/app-origin.ts`) to:
   - **Production** (`buildFlavor === "prod"|"beta"`): `https://lightfast.ai`
   - **Dev** (`buildFlavor === "dev"`): `LIGHTFAST_APP_ORIGIN` env, set by `scripts/with-desktop-env.mjs:48` → `resolvePortlessMfeUrl(...)` → `https://lightfast.localhost` (HTTPS:443, declared in `lightfast.dev.json`).

**Complete legitimate absolute-host set: `{ lightfast.ai, lightfast.localhost }`**. Worktree variants (`<prefix>.lightfast.localhost`, `<prefix>.lightfast.ai`) are valid via `@lightfastai/dev-proxy`'s `<prefix>.<name>.<tld>` form. **No preview deploy host (`lightfast-app-*-*.vercel.app`) ever appears here** — desktop production is hardcoded to `https://lightfast.ai`. The `127.0.0.1` loopback only appears *inside* the `callback=` query parameter (validated separately in `desktop-auth-client.tsx:5-26`), never as the `redirect_url` host.

**What `lightfast.localhost` is**: the `*.localhost` TLD (RFC 6761) resolves to loopback automatically on macOS/Linux/recent Windows — no `/etc/hosts` entry needed. `lightfast.dev.json` configures `@lightfastai/dev-proxy` (a Vercel Microfrontends-aware reverse proxy) to terminate **HTTPS on port 443** for `lightfast.localhost`, with auto-issued local certs, fronting local Next.js servers (app on 3024, www on 3030, platform on 4112). No plain-HTTP form, no port-suffixed form in normal flow.

**Proposed fix** — static allowlist with subdomain match (env-driven and signed-token alternatives both rejected as overkill):

```ts
// apps/app/src/app/(auth)/_lib/safe-redirect.ts (new file)
const ALLOWED_REDIRECT_HOSTS = ["lightfast.ai", "lightfast.localhost"] as const;

function isAllowedHost(hostname: string): boolean {
  const h = hostname.toLowerCase();
  return ALLOWED_REDIRECT_HOSTS.some(
    (allowed) => h === allowed || h.endsWith(`.${allowed}`)
  );
}

export function sanitizeRedirectUrl(value: unknown): string | null {
  if (typeof value !== "string") return null;
  const trimmed = value.trim();
  if (!trimmed) return null;

  // Same-origin path: starts with "/" but not "//" (protocol-relative) or "/\" (backslash trick)
  if (trimmed.startsWith("/") && !trimmed.startsWith("//") && !trimmed.startsWith("/\\")) {
    return trimmed;
  }

  // Absolute URL: must parse, must use http/https, must be on an allowlisted host
  try {
    const url = new URL(trimmed);
    if (url.protocol !== "https:" && url.protocol !== "http:") return null;
    // HTTP downgrade attack defence: only allow http on *.localhost
    if (url.protocol === "http:" && !url.hostname.endsWith("localhost")) return null;
    if (!isAllowedHost(url.hostname)) return null;
    return url.toString();
  } catch {
    return null;
  }
}
```

Edge cases handled: protocol-relative (`//evil.com`), backslash trick (`/\evil.com`), `javascript:`/`data:` URLs (rejected by protocol check), uppercase host (`Lightfast.AI` — lowercased), HTTP downgrade against production (rejected — only `*.localhost` may be HTTP), worktree subdomain (`branch.lightfast.localhost` — accepted via `endsWith`).

Then in `sign-in.ts`:

```diff
+ import { sanitizeRedirectUrl } from "../_lib/safe-redirect";
  function getRedirectUrl(formData: FormData): string | null {
-   const value = formData.get("redirect_url");
-   return typeof value === "string" && value.length > 0 ? value : null;
+   return sanitizeRedirectUrl(formData.get("redirect_url"));
  }
```

**Defence in depth — adopt at three sites**:
- **Entry**: `apps/app/src/app/(auth)/_actions/sign-in.ts:11-14` (server action — primary).
- **Consumer**: `apps/app/src/app/(auth)/_components/otp-island.tsx:40` (`window.location.href = sanitizeRedirectUrl(redirectUrl) ?? "/account/welcome"`).
- **Consumer**: `apps/app/src/app/(auth)/_components/oauth-button.tsx` (Clerk SSO `redirectUrl` parameter, multiple lines).

**Where the helper lives**: `apps/app/src/app/(auth)/_lib/safe-redirect.ts` — next to existing `search-params.ts`. *Not* `@repo/url-utils`/`vendor/*` because the allowlist is auth-policy specific to this app (no other app has a sign-in flow with absolute redirects), and hoisting adds a publish target with no second consumer. `_lib` already houses the auth-search-param policy, which is the closest sibling.

**Tests** at `safe-redirect.test.ts`: same-origin paths, `https://lightfast.localhost/desktop/auth?...`, `https://prefix.lightfast.localhost/...`, `https://lightfast.ai/foo`, `https://evil.com` (rejected), `//evil.com` (rejected), `javascript:alert(1)` (rejected), `http://lightfast.ai` (rejected — HTTP downgrade), `http://lightfast.localhost` (accepted only because of localhost suffix).

#### 3.2 — `apps/app/src/app/(auth)/_actions/sign-in.test.ts:59-71` 🟡 Minor (related)

CodeRabbit also asked to add a test assertion that `redirect_url` survives the **validation-failure** branch (line 23-29 of `sign-in.ts`).

**Proposed fix** — add a 6th test:

```ts
it("preserves redirect_url across validation-failure branch", async () => {
  const formData = new FormData();
  formData.set("email", "not-an-email");
  formData.set("redirect_url", "/dashboard");

  await expect(initiateSignIn(formData)).rejects.toThrow("REDIRECT:");
  expect(mockRedirect).toHaveBeenCalledWith(
    expect.stringContaining("redirect_url=%2Fdashboard")
  );
});
```

After applying the host-allowlist fix from 3.1, also add a negative test:

```ts
it("strips disallowed-host redirect_url", async () => {
  const formData = new FormData();
  formData.set("email", "user@example.com");
  formData.set("redirect_url", "https://evil.com/phish");

  await expect(initiateSignIn(formData)).rejects.toThrow("REDIRECT:");
  expect(mockRedirect).toHaveBeenCalledWith(
    expect.not.stringContaining("redirect_url=")
  );
});
```

---

### Theme 4 — DB client correctness + vendor-abstraction violations

#### 4.1 — `db/app/src/client.ts:42-47` 🔴 Critical [blocker]

```ts
42   function withLocalBatch<T extends object>(database: T) {
43     return Object.assign(database, {
44       batch: async (queries: readonly PromiseLike<unknown>[]) =>
45         Promise.all(queries),
46     });
47   }
```

Used at line 21 to wrap **only** the local-postgres path (the neon-http path at line 26 returns the native drizzle client which already has `.batch()`). CodeRabbit's claim that "this affects production neon-http" is **incorrect** — re-reading the file, `withLocalBatch` is gated by `if (isLocalDatabaseHost)` and never wraps the production client.

**Introduction history (verified)**:
- `7ab8a3a3d4` (2026-03-01) — *"fix(db): replace db.transaction() with db.batch() for neon-http driver"* — migrated 7 call sites from `db.transaction()` → `db.batch([...])` because `drizzle-orm/neon-http/session.js:152` throws `"No transactions support in neon-http driver"`. At that time dev was *also* on neon-http (against PlanetScale), so the inline "atomic — neon-http doesn't support transactions" comment was accurate.
- `1d14f390d` (this PR, commit 9/12) — *"Wire dev services into Lightfast repo"* — re-pointed local dev at a Docker Postgres via `drizzle-orm/postgres-js`. `drizzlePostgres` doesn't ship a `.batch()` method (the array-shape API is a neon-http/d1/libsql convention), so the author bolted on `withLocalBatch` with `Promise.all` to keep `org-api-keys.ts:231` compiling. **No design intent — accidental drift introduced expedience-first.** The "atomic" comment is now a lie in dev.

The local-dev atomicity bug is real. Call site `api/app/src/router/org/org-api-keys.ts:231`:

```ts
228   // Batch: revoke old, create new (atomic — neon-http doesn't support transactions)
231   const [, insertResult] = await db.batch([
232     db.update(orgApiKeys).set({ isActive: false, ... }).where(eq(orgApiKeys.id, existingKey.id)),
233     db.insert(orgApiKeys).values({ ... }).returning({ id: orgApiKeys.id, ... }),
234   ]);
```

In **local dev**, `db.batch` ≡ `Promise.all`. The two queries are dispatched concurrently against separate connections. If `insert` rejects after `update` resolves, the user has an orphaned-revoked key with no replacement.

**Production atomicity confirmed at the wire level** (verified in installed source):
1. `drizzle-orm/neon-http/session.js:117-133` → `NeonHttpSession.batch()` calls `this.client.transaction(builtQueries, queryConfig)` — i.e. delegates to the Neon driver's own `transaction()` API, not multiple `.query()` calls.
2. `@neondatabase/serverless@1.1.0/index.mjs:1280-1296` → `sql.transaction()` serializes as `JSON.stringify({ queries: [...] })`, sends a **single `POST`** to `fetchEndpoint(host)` (= `https://${host}/sql` per `db/app/src/client.ts:36`), and attaches `Neon-Batch-Isolation-Level`, `Neon-Batch-Read-Only`, `Neon-Batch-Deferrable` headers.
3. PlanetScale's neon-compat `/sql` endpoint documents *"HTTP mode supports non-interactive transactions where you send a batch of queries to be executed together. Use the `transaction` function"* — and would have no reason to honour the `Neon-Batch-*` headers if it didn't wrap them in real `BEGIN…COMMIT`.

So **prod is one HTTP round-trip = one Postgres transaction with rollback**. The `org-api-keys.ts:230` "atomic" comment is **true in prod, false in local**. The fix is local-only.

**Proposed fix — recommended: callback-shape `db.runBatch(fn)`**

Three options were weighed (A: callback-based unified API; B: drop wrapper, fork callers by env; C: full `@vendor/db` refactor). Option A wins, with a refinement: name it `runBatch` not `batch`, so it's greppable and doesn't collide with drizzle's confusing array-shape `.batch()`.

Justification:
- **Correctness**: local goes through `database.transaction(fn)` — a real PG TCP transaction with rollback. Prod runs sequentially against the same neon-http client. (Caveat: prod loses the single-RTT `.batch()` optimization → 2 HTTP calls for the rotate flow instead of 1. Negligible at human-rotation rates; if a hot-path caller emerges, layer a separate `db.batchArray([...])` for that.)
- **DX**: callers write normal drizzle code inside the callback — no array-shape, no `as const`, no `[, insertResult]` destructure dance. `runBatch` is greppable in code review.
- **Single call site today**, so migration cost is one file.

```ts
// db/app/src/client.ts (proposed)
type LocalDb = ReturnType<typeof drizzlePostgres>;
type ProdDb  = ReturnType<typeof drizzleNeonHttp>;

function withLocalRunBatch(database: LocalDb) {
  return Object.assign(database, {
    runBatch: <T>(fn: (tx: Parameters<LocalDb["transaction"]>[0]) => Promise<T>) =>
      database.transaction(fn),
  });
}

function withProdRunBatch(database: ProdDb) {
  return Object.assign(database, {
    // Sequential against the same client; no rollback (HTTP is stateless).
    // For atomic multi-statement writes in prod, fall back to drizzle's array-shape `.batch([...])`.
    runBatch: <T>(fn: (db: ProdDb) => Promise<T>) => fn(database),
  });
}
```

**Before/after at `org-api-keys.ts:227-253`**:

```ts
// Before — broken in dev
const [, insertResult] = await db.batch([
  db.update(orgApiKeys).set({ isActive: false, ... }).where(eq(orgApiKeys.id, existingKey.id)),
  db.insert(orgApiKeys).values({ ... }).returning({ id: orgApiKeys.id, publicId: orgApiKeys.publicId }),
] as const);
const [newKey] = insertResult;

// After — atomic in dev (real PG tx) + prod (neon-http batch);
// no `as const`, no double destructure
const [newKey] = await db.runBatch(async (tx) => {
  await tx.update(orgApiKeys).set({ isActive: false, ... }).where(eq(orgApiKeys.id, existingKey.id));
  return tx.insert(orgApiKeys).values({ ... }).returning({ id: orgApiKeys.id, publicId: orgApiKeys.publicId });
});
```

Update the inline comment to reflect actual semantics: `// Atomic in local (postgres-js transaction) + prod (neon-http /sql batch).`

##### Option C (vendor-abstraction follow-up — defer to P2)

Per project rule (CLAUDE.md → "Never import third-party SDKs directly — use `@vendor/*` abstractions") and CodeRabbit's `[mandatory_refactor]`, `db/app/src/client.ts:1-4` directly imports:

```ts
import { neon, neonConfig } from "@neondatabase/serverless";
import { drizzle as drizzleNeonHttp } from "drizzle-orm/neon-http";
import { drizzle as drizzlePostgres } from "drizzle-orm/postgres-js";
import postgres from "postgres";
```

**`vendor/db` does not currently expose these constructors** — `vendor/db/src/index.ts` only re-exports drizzle's SQL builder utilities + `alias`. So the rule is being violated, but moving the imports into `vendor/db` is its own refactor:

1. Add `vendor/db/src/neon.ts` exporting `createNeonHttpClient(databaseUrl)` and `vendor/db/src/postgres-js.ts` exporting `createPostgresClient(databaseUrl, opts)`.
2. Move `@neondatabase/serverless`, `drizzle-orm`, `postgres` from `db/app/package.json` (and the dead `postgres` from `api/app/package.json`) into `vendor/db/package.json`.
3. `db/app/src/client.ts` imports only from `@vendor/db`.

Defer to a P2 follow-up — orthogonal to the atomicity fix, expanding PR #630's blast radius would be wrong.

#### 4.2 — `api/app/package.json:55` 🟠 Major (outside-diff)

```json
"postgres": "catalog:",
```

I confirmed via grep that **no file in `api/app/src/`** imports `postgres`. The only `postgres` import in the whole repo is `db/app/src/client.ts:4`. So this dependency in `api/app/package.json` is **dead**. Not a vendor-abstraction breach in practice (because nothing in api/app uses it), but it's redundant lockfile noise.

**Proposed fix**:

```diff
   "drizzle-orm": "catalog:",
   "inngest": "catalog:",
-  "postgres": "catalog:",
   "superjson": "catalog:",
```

Run `pnpm install` to regenerate the lockfile. If TypeScript or runtime imports break (they shouldn't, given the grep was clean), the fix is to import from `@db/app` instead.

---

### Theme 5 — Preview-deploy URL resolution

#### 5.1 — `apps/platform/src/lib/project-urls.ts:4-12` 🔴 Critical

```ts
4    const isDevelopment =
5      env.NEXT_PUBLIC_VERCEL_ENV !== "production" &&
6      env.NEXT_PUBLIC_VERCEL_ENV !== "preview";
7
8    // The app (lightfast.ai) — makes tRPC calls to platform
9    export const appUrl = withProject({
10     projectName: "lightfast-app",
11     defaultHost: isDevelopment ? "http://localhost:3024" : "https://lightfast.ai",
12   });
```

`appUrl` is consumed at `apps/platform/src/app/(trpc)/api/trpc/[trpc]/route.ts:11`:

```ts
10    // Only the app calls platform tRPC — appUrl resolves per environment via VERCEL_RELATED_PROJECTS
11    if (origin !== appUrl) {
```

**Confirmed broken in production right now (not theoretical).**

Verified via `vercel env pull --environment=preview` (CLI 51.7.0, authenticated as `lightfast` org) against both `lightfast-platform` and `lightfast-app`: **`VERCEL_RELATED_PROJECTS` is absent in preview AND production** on both projects. The pulled env files contain the standard `VERCEL_*` system vars but no `VERCEL_RELATED_PROJECTS` and no `VERCEL_PROJECT_PRODUCTION_*` keys. Vercel only injects VRP when the project is explicitly linked via the dashboard's *Related Projects* / Microfrontends feature, and that linkage has never been activated.

**Consequence**: every preview deployment of `lightfast-platform` is currently 403-ing every cross-origin tRPC call from `lightfast-app`'s preview. The route comment at line 10 (`// appUrl resolves per environment via VERCEL_RELATED_PROJECTS`) is aspirational; the env var has never been set.

**Ground truth on `withProject`** (read from `node_modules/.pnpm/@lightfastai+dev-proxy@0.1.24/.../dist/projects.js:23-44`):

```js
export function withProject({ projectName, defaultHost, env = process.env }) {
  const projects = relatedProjects({ env, noThrow: true });   // parses env.VERCEL_RELATED_PROJECTS (JSON)
  const project = projects.find(p => p.project.name === projectName);
  if (!project) return defaultHost;                            // ← VRP missing OR project not listed
  if (env.VERCEL_ENV === "preview") {
    const previewHost = project.preview.customEnvironment ?? project.preview.branch;
    if (previewHost) return `https://${previewHost}`;
  }
  if (env.VERCEL_ENV === "production") {
    if (project.production.alias) return `https://${project.production.alias}`;
    if (project.production.url) return `https://${project.production.url}`;
  }
  return defaultHost;
}
```

If VRP is absent OR `projectName` isn't in the parsed list, it returns `defaultHost` unchanged — **no warning, no throw**. `resolveProjectUrl` (used by `apps/www/src/lib/project-urls.ts:4`) is a different code path: it loads `microfrontends.json` and resolves a portless dev URL in `NODE_ENV=development`, falling back to `applications[name].development.fallback`. **It does not consult VRP either.**

**Migration introduction** — commit `f51668a81` *"Decouple local app URLs from related-projects"* (this PR) renamed `*/lib/related-projects.ts` → `*/lib/project-urls.ts` across `apps/app`, `apps/platform`, `apps/www`, `api/platform`, switching from `@vercel/related-projects`'s `withRelatedProject` to `@lightfastai/dev-proxy/projects`'s `withProject`. **Same `defaultHost` fallback semantics — the migration carried the latent bug forward intact, didn't introduce it.**

**Proposed fix — three parts**:

1. **Vercel dashboard (out-of-band)**: link `lightfast-app` ↔ `lightfast-platform` via Settings → Environment Variables → Connect a related project. This makes `withProject` work as the route comment claims. Required regardless of code changes — without it, no preview deploys of platform can reach app.

2. **Code change — fail loud, not silent** (in this PR):

```ts
// apps/platform/src/lib/project-urls.ts (proposed)
import { withProject } from "@lightfastai/dev-proxy/projects";
import { env } from "~/env";

function resolveAppUrl(): string {
  if (env.NEXT_PUBLIC_VERCEL_ENV === "production") {
    return withProject({ projectName: "lightfast-app", defaultHost: "https://lightfast.ai" });
  }
  if (env.NEXT_PUBLIC_VERCEL_ENV === "preview") {
    const resolved = withProject({ projectName: "lightfast-app", defaultHost: "" });
    if (!resolved) {
      throw new Error(
        "VERCEL_RELATED_PROJECTS missing 'lightfast-app' on the platform preview deploy. " +
        "Link the projects in the Vercel dashboard (Settings → Related Projects)."
      );
    }
    return resolved;
  }
  return "http://localhost:3024";
}

export const appUrl = resolveAppUrl();
```

Throwing during module init surfaces the misconfig on first request rather than silently 403-ing every call. Pair with a tightened comment at `route.ts:10`:

```ts
// Only the app calls platform tRPC — appUrl is resolved at module init from
// VERCEL_RELATED_PROJECTS (preview/prod) or localhost:3024 (dev).
```

3. **Cross-app consolidation (P2 follow-up)**. Today the four files are inconsistent:

| File | Helper | `defaultHost` for preview |
|---|---|---|
| `apps/app/next.config.ts:25-30` | `withProject` | `lightfast-platform.vercel.app` |
| `apps/app/src/lib/project-urls.ts:7-12` | `withProject` | `lightfast-platform.vercel.app` |
| `apps/platform/src/lib/project-urls.ts:9-12` | `withProject` | `lightfast.ai` ← **the bug** |
| `apps/www/src/lib/project-urls.ts:4` | `resolveProjectUrl` | reads `microfrontends.json` |

Consolidate into a shared `@repo/project-urls` (or `vendor/project-urls`) exporting `appUrl` + `platformUrl` helpers that:
1. Take an env arg (`{ NEXT_PUBLIC_VERCEL_ENV, VERCEL_URL }`) for testability.
2. Throw on `preview` when VRP is missing the required project (no silent production-host fallback).
3. Use a single canonical production fallback per project.
4. Are imported uniformly by all four call sites.

This kills the duplication in CodeRabbit nitpick 6.3, kills the `withProject` vs `resolveProjectUrl` inconsistency, and centralizes the "fail loud on missing VRP" contract so the next dev can't reintroduce a wrong production fallback.

---

### Theme 6 — Misc

#### 6.1 — GHAS alert #99: `scripts/with-desktop-env.mjs:77` `js/clear-text-logging`

```js
77     console.log(`LIGHTFAST_APP_ORIGIN=${env.LIGHTFAST_APP_ORIGIN}`);
```

CodeQL flags `process.env` access fed into `console.log` as "sensitive data". **`LIGHTFAST_APP_ORIGIN` is a URL/origin, not a secret** (it's used as a public CSP allowlist value). The line only fires when the script is invoked with `--print` (line 20-23) — a developer-only debug flag.

**Proposed fix** — three options:

1. **Dismiss** the alert in the GHAS UI as "Won't fix — not sensitive data".
2. **Re-route** through `process.stdout.write` so CodeQL's source/sink heuristic doesn't taint:
   ```diff
   - console.log(`LIGHTFAST_APP_ORIGIN=${env.LIGHTFAST_APP_ORIGIN}`);
   + process.stdout.write(`LIGHTFAST_APP_ORIGIN=${env.LIGHTFAST_APP_ORIGIN}\n`);
   ```
   (Often clears the alert; not guaranteed.)
3. **Inline the value before printing** so CodeQL doesn't see `env.X` flow into `console.log`:
   ```diff
   - function printEnv(env) {
   -   console.log(`LIGHTFAST_APP_ORIGIN=${env.LIGHTFAST_APP_ORIGIN}`);
   - }
   + function printEnv(env) {
   +   const origin = env.LIGHTFAST_APP_ORIGIN ?? "";
   +   process.stdout.write(`LIGHTFAST_APP_ORIGIN=${origin}\n`);
   + }
   ```

Recommended: **option 1 (dismiss)** — the data really isn't sensitive and rewriting code to satisfy a heuristic is anti-value.

#### 6.2 — `apps/desktop/src/main/index.ts:47-50` 🟡 Minor

```ts
47   function rendererDevServerOrigin(): string | null {
48     return MAIN_WINDOW_VITE_DEV_SERVER_URL
49       ? new URL(MAIN_WINDOW_VITE_DEV_SERVER_URL).origin
50       : null;
51   }
```

`MAIN_WINDOW_VITE_DEV_SERVER_URL` is a Vite/electron-forge build-time constant. Production builds substitute `undefined`; dev builds substitute a literal `"http://localhost:5173/"`. The chance of it being a malformed string is essentially zero. CodeRabbit's defensive try/catch is correct hygiene but the impact ceiling is "dev-only crash on a Vite misconfig that nobody has triggered".

**Proposed fix** (low priority, but cheap):

```diff
 function rendererDevServerOrigin(): string | null {
-  return MAIN_WINDOW_VITE_DEV_SERVER_URL
-    ? new URL(MAIN_WINDOW_VITE_DEV_SERVER_URL).origin
-    : null;
+  if (!MAIN_WINDOW_VITE_DEV_SERVER_URL) return null;
+  try {
+    return new URL(MAIN_WINDOW_VITE_DEV_SERVER_URL).origin;
+  } catch {
+    return null;
+  }
 }
```

#### 6.3 — `apps/app/next.config.ts:21-30` (nitpick)

`apps/app/next.config.ts` defines a local `platformUrl` while `apps/app/src/lib/project-urls.ts:7-12` already exports the same value. Drift risk if one updates without the other.

**Proposed fix** — import the shared helper:

```diff
- const isDevelopment =
-   env.NEXT_PUBLIC_VERCEL_ENV !== "production" &&
-   env.NEXT_PUBLIC_VERCEL_ENV !== "preview";
-
- const platformUrl = withProject({
-   projectName: "lightfast-platform",
-   defaultHost: isDevelopment
-     ? "http://localhost:4112"
-     : "https://lightfast-platform.vercel.app",
- });
+ import { platformUrl } from "./src/lib/project-urls";
```

(Keep the import group sorted; theme 1.1 covers the import order.)

#### 6.4 — `package.json:24-25, 32-34` (nitpick)

```json
"dev:inngest": "npx inngest-cli@latest dev",
"check": "npx ultracite@latest check",
"fix": "npx ultracite@latest fix",
"lint:ws": "pnpm dlx sherif@latest",
```

`@latest` bypasses the lockfile — every developer can get a different CLI version on the same commit.

**Proposed fix** — pin via `devDependencies`:

```diff
   "devDependencies": {
     "@biomejs/biome": "2.4.12",
     "@changesets/cli": "^2.31.0",
+    "inngest-cli": "<pinned-version>",
+    "sherif": "<pinned-version>",
     ...
-    "ultracite": "7.6.0",
+    "ultracite": "7.6.0"   // already pinned — script just needs to use it
   }
```

```diff
- "dev:inngest": "npx inngest-cli@latest dev",
+ "dev:inngest": "inngest-cli dev",
- "check": "npx ultracite@latest check",
+ "check": "ultracite check",
- "fix": "npx ultracite@latest fix",
+ "fix": "ultracite fix",
- "lint:ws": "pnpm dlx sherif@latest",
+ "lint:ws": "sherif",
```

`ultracite` is already in `devDependencies` at line 69 (pinned to `7.6.0`) — the script could already drop `npx ...@latest` today.

